WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.964 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.964 --> 00:00:12.450 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:24.758 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.758 --> 00:00:26.550 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:27.390 align:middle line:90%
I'm George Noory.

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:29.460 align:middle line:10%
Our special guest
today is Patrick Wood.

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:31.380 align:middle line:10%
Patrick is an
author, lecturer who

00:00:31.380 --> 00:00:36.570 align:middle line:10%
has studied elite globalization
policies since the late 1970s,

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:38.220 align:middle line:10%
and to this day
remains a leading

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:42.790 align:middle line:10%
expert on the elitist trilateral
commission-- their policies,

00:00:42.790 --> 00:00:45.090 align:middle line:10%
their achievements,
and what they do.

00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:46.780 align:middle line:90%
Patrick, welcome to the program.

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:47.190 align:middle line:90%
>>PATRICK WOOD: Hi, George.

00:00:47.190 --> 00:00:48.000 align:middle line:90%
Nice to be here with you.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.917 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How long have
you been studying this?

00:00:49.917 --> 00:00:51.060 align:middle line:90%
Truly since the '70s?

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:52.920 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Truly since
the 1970s, George.

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:54.100 align:middle line:90%
It's been a long trip.

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:54.900 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:56.010 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: And I'm not
done with my mission,

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:57.400 align:middle line:84%
apparently, because
I'm still here

00:00:57.400 --> 00:00:58.330 align:middle line:90%
and I'm still talking about it.

00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:00.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And they're still
letting you talk about it.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:02.040 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: They're still letting
me talk about it as well.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:04.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did you
get involved in this?

00:01:04.050 --> 00:01:07.785 align:middle line:10%
>>WOOD: I ran into a
gentleman-- a professor

00:01:07.785 --> 00:01:10.340 align:middle line:10%
that had just been separated
from the Hoover Institution

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:11.140 align:middle line:10%
at Stanford.

00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:12.900 align:middle line:10%
His name was Antony Sutton.

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:14.730 align:middle line:10%
He was a research fellow.

00:01:14.730 --> 00:01:17.370 align:middle line:84%
And he was studying the
Trilateral Commission while

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:21.690 align:middle line:84%
at Hoover, not realizing that
the president of Stanford

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:25.560 align:middle line:84%
University was a member of
the Trilateral Commission.

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:28.230 align:middle line:90%
They didn't want him studying--

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:30.720 align:middle line:84%
especially with the
Hoover Institution--

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:31.560 align:middle line:90%
this topic.

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:33.570 align:middle line:90%
So they kind of forced him out.

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:41.430 align:middle line:84%
And I ran into him at a gold
conference down in Louisiana,

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:43.060 align:middle line:90%
kind of by chance on one hand--

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:44.727 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it was
chance, personally.

00:01:44.727 --> 00:01:46.920 align:middle line:84%
But I ran into him
at a restaurant

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:49.500 align:middle line:84%
at a convention
we were attending.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.540 align:middle line:84%
We struck up a
conversation, realized

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:53.910 align:middle line:84%
that we were both kind of
looking at the same group.

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:56.430 align:middle line:90%
This was 1977.

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.560 align:middle line:84%
And before that
breakfast was done,

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.520 align:middle line:84%
we had shaken hands that
we needed to tell a story,

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:03.500 align:middle line:90%
that it was that big.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.640 align:middle line:84%
And so we started to
publish a newsletter.

00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:07.230 align:middle line:84%
We eventually
published two books--

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:09.090 align:middle line:90%
"Trilaterals Over Washington."

00:02:09.090 --> 00:02:13.530 align:middle line:84%
And gosh, we spoke on
hundreds of radio programs

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:16.230 align:middle line:84%
around the country, and
in-person groups, and stuff,

00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:19.500 align:middle line:84%
to try and elevate
the discussion.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.465 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How many
people believe it?

00:02:21.465 --> 00:02:23.340 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Well, you know,
pretty much everybody

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:27.170 align:middle line:84%
that heard us in person believed
our material, because it

00:02:27.170 --> 00:02:28.680 align:middle line:90%
was very factual.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:31.970 align:middle line:84%
We only took the information
from the Trilateral Commission

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:34.100 align:middle line:90%
itself and their own people.

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:36.660 align:middle line:84%
We analyzed it and
wrote about that.

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:42.560 align:middle line:84%
But as far as people who
hadn't heard us in person,

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:44.060 align:middle line:84%
members of the
Trilateral Commission

00:02:44.060 --> 00:02:46.310 align:middle line:84%
did a very good job
of marginalizing us

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:48.040 align:middle line:84%
as either the far
right or the far left.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:48.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Or a conspiracy--

00:02:48.650 --> 00:02:49.750 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: They didn't
know which we were.

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:50.918 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --theorist, right?

00:02:50.918 --> 00:02:52.460 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: But it didn't
matter to them.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:54.243 align:middle line:84%
It left them always
in the modern middle.

00:02:54.243 --> 00:02:55.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:56.840 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: And we were
always either swept

00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:59.510 align:middle line:84%
off this way or
this way, as being

00:02:59.510 --> 00:03:00.920 align:middle line:90%
irrelevant to the discussion.

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:03.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, the folks who
are watching this program right

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:07.820 align:middle line:84%
now have probably heard of
the Trilateral Commission.

00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:10.250 align:middle line:84%
But they may not
know what it is.

00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:11.900 align:middle line:90%
What is it?

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:14.570 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Well, it was an
elite organization, for sure,

00:03:14.570 --> 00:03:18.780 align:middle line:84%
founded by David Rockefeller
and Zbigniew Brzezinski in 1973.

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:20.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Aha.

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:24.680 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: The membership was
drawn from Japan, North America,

00:03:24.680 --> 00:03:28.610 align:middle line:84%
and Europe in roughly
equal numbers.

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:33.150 align:middle line:84%
There were government officials
represented, lots of--

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:33.950 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Scholars.

00:03:33.950 --> 00:03:37.850 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Law firms, scholars,
multinational corporation

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:40.730 align:middle line:84%
directors, CEOs, stuff
like that-- very wealthy,

00:03:40.730 --> 00:03:42.470 align:middle line:90%
moneyed people.

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:46.400 align:middle line:84%
Those were kind of the
global merchants of the day.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:49.550 align:middle line:84%
And there was a few
press people as well,

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:51.620 align:middle line:84%
like Time Magazine,
Newsweek, and so on,

00:03:51.620 --> 00:03:53.180 align:middle line:90%
that were part of it.

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:56.810 align:middle line:84%
And they came
together, ostensibly,

00:03:56.810 --> 00:04:00.020 align:middle line:84%
to create a new
international economic order.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:01.730 align:middle line:90%
That was on their literature.

00:04:01.730 --> 00:04:04.790 align:middle line:84%
And that's ultimately
what piqued my interest.

00:04:04.790 --> 00:04:06.360 align:middle line:84%
We wrote a lot about
that back then.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:09.468 align:middle line:84%
What was the new
international economic order?

00:04:09.468 --> 00:04:10.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And what was the goal?

00:04:10.760 --> 00:04:12.860 align:middle line:90%
>>WOOD: What was the goal of it?

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:14.810 align:middle line:84%
Sutton and I didn't
really get it back then,

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:18.529 align:middle line:84%
because we not understand
historic technocracy.

00:04:18.529 --> 00:04:21.410 align:middle line:84%
Had we understood
it and studied it,

00:04:21.410 --> 00:04:25.410 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure we would have put the
dots together at that point.

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:28.670 align:middle line:84%
But I really didn't discover
historic technocracy

00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:33.620 align:middle line:84%
until after Professor
Sutton passed in 2002--

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:36.400 align:middle line:90%
and picked up the trail again.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.890 align:middle line:84%
OK, this is how-- this is what
they had in mind back then.

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:45.020 align:middle line:84%
But both Brzezinski
and Rockefeller

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:49.940 align:middle line:84%
were kind of the cream of the
crop, the Beauty and the Beast.

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:53.398 align:middle line:84%
Brzezinski was the brains,
and Rockefeller had the money.

00:04:53.398 --> 00:04:55.440 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He was the Carter
administration, right?

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:56.240 align:middle line:90%
At the time.

00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:59.390 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: He was very instrumental
throughout the Carter

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:01.070 align:middle line:90%
administration.

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:08.970 align:middle line:84%
But during that administration,
Carter inducted almost a third

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:12.350 align:middle line:84%
of the US membership of
the Trilateral Commission

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:15.183 align:middle line:90%
into his cabinet at one time.

00:05:15.183 --> 00:05:17.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Based on
Brzezinski's recommendation.

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:20.720 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Based on Brzezinski's
recommendation, exactly.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:23.120 align:middle line:84%
Brzezinski was the first
appointee, by the way.

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:26.870 align:middle line:84%
And both Carter and Mondale
were members of the commission

00:05:26.870 --> 00:05:28.440 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:30.860 align:middle line:84%
But Brzezinski was
the first appointee

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:32.068 align:middle line:90%
to national security advisor.

00:05:32.068 --> 00:05:33.693 align:middle line:84%
He was the gatekeeper
to the president.

00:05:33.693 --> 00:05:34.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He was, exactly.

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:37.040 align:middle line:90%
Now, what is technocracy?

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:44.120 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Technocracy was an
economic system developed

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:48.710 align:middle line:84%
in the 1930s by a group of
scientists and engineers

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:50.690 align:middle line:90%
at Columbia University.

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:53.540 align:middle line:84%
There was talk about
technocracy during the '20s,

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:58.040 align:middle line:84%
but it kind of formally
got together officially,

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:01.052 align:middle line:84%
if you will, in 1932
at Columbia University.

00:06:01.052 --> 00:06:02.760 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So it's been
around a long time.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:04.730 align:middle line:90%
>>WOOD: It was a long time ago.

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:06.710 align:middle line:84%
That was during the
Great Depression.

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:09.410 align:middle line:84%
Everybody thought
capitalism was dead.

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:13.070 align:middle line:84%
And the scientists and
engineers at Columbia

00:06:13.070 --> 00:06:17.830 align:middle line:84%
felt like it was up to
them to save the world.

00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:22.980 align:middle line:84%
So they modeled an economic
system, from the ground up,

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:27.100 align:middle line:84%
to be a resource-based economic
system, controlled by energy.

00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:28.950 align:middle line:84%
And you have to
understand, this had never

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:30.910 align:middle line:84%
been attempted in the
history of the world.

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:34.652 align:middle line:84%
There had never been an economic
system developed from scratch.

00:06:34.652 --> 00:06:35.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: For the world.

00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:37.290 align:middle line:90%
>>WOOD: For the world.

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:38.940 align:middle line:90%
But they did.

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And it fizzled, I have to
say, by the end of the--

00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:43.800 align:middle line:84%
certainly by the
mid-'40s, it fizzled.

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:47.850 align:middle line:84%
World War II is well underway,
and capitalism revived.

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:50.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now was the Federal
Reserve part of any of this?

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:54.030 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Oh, it was all there
during that period of time,

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:57.270 align:middle line:84%
still running the
capital system.

00:06:57.270 --> 00:06:59.100 align:middle line:84%
That's one of the
reasons, I suppose,

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:03.270 align:middle line:84%
that technocracy didn't quite
make it as far as they hoped.

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:05.070 align:middle line:90%
But it didn't.

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:06.390 align:middle line:90%
That was a good thing.

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:09.450 align:middle line:84%
It went underground
for a period of time

00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:14.490 align:middle line:84%
during the '40 and the '50s,
and even into the '60s.

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:17.430 align:middle line:10%
But when Brzezinski
wrote his seminal book,

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:18.840 align:middle line:10%
called, "Between Two Ages--

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:22.050 align:middle line:10%
America's Role in the
Technotronic Era,"

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:26.820 align:middle line:10%
Brzezinski was a professor
at Columbia University.

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:27.850 align:middle line:90%
Is that a coincidence?

00:07:27.850 --> 00:07:29.160 align:middle line:90%
Maybe.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:33.363 align:middle line:84%
But the halls of academia
talk about stuff.

00:07:33.363 --> 00:07:35.280 align:middle line:84%
They talk about the
history of the university,

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:37.150 align:middle line:90%
and what happened, and so on.

00:07:37.150 --> 00:07:40.320 align:middle line:84%
So there's no doubt in
my mind that Brzezinski

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:43.260 align:middle line:84%
had an awareness of exactly
what technocracy was.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, let's take
a look at technocracy.

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:48.530 align:middle line:90%
>>WOOD: You bet.

00:07:48.530 --> 00:07:49.970 align:middle line:10%
>>NARRATOR:
Technocracy advocates

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.670 align:middle line:10%
argue the democratic
system is unprofessional,

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:56.460 align:middle line:10%
overly politicized,
corrupt and ineffective.

00:07:56.460 --> 00:07:59.090 align:middle line:10%
A society managed by
scientists and engineers

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:01.880 align:middle line:10%
would be more rational
and productive.

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:04.220 align:middle line:10%
Singaporeans handed
rule of their society

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:06.740 align:middle line:10%
to a one-party
technocracy, and it's

00:08:06.740 --> 00:08:10.130 align:middle line:10%
an economic powerhouse with
the second-busiest port

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:14.510 align:middle line:10%
and the third-highest per
capita income in the world.

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:16.310 align:middle line:10%
Ukraine's outgoing
economy minister

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:19.940 align:middle line:10%
called technocracy "the only
hope for lasting change,"

00:08:19.940 --> 00:08:22.870 align:middle line:10%
two years after the
2014 revolution,

00:08:22.870 --> 00:08:25.972 align:middle line:10%
when people were growing tired
of the slow pace of reform.

00:08:25.972 --> 00:08:27.680 align:middle line:10%
>>AIVARAS ABROMAVICIUS:
I think we really

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:30.320 align:middle line:10%
need to use this
opportunity to bring

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:35.659 align:middle line:10%
in a completely different set
of people with a completely

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:37.265 align:middle line:10%
different mindset.

00:08:37.265 --> 00:08:40.130 align:middle line:10%
>>NARRATOR: In 2011,
both Rome and Athens

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:42.110 align:middle line:10%
installed prime
ministers with expertise

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:45.800 align:middle line:10%
in economics and finance to
drive through tough austerity

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:47.090 align:middle line:10%
measures.

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:49.460 align:middle line:10%
Technocracy does
have its proponents.

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:51.150 align:middle line:10%
Pew Research shows
that while there's

00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:53.960 align:middle line:10%
a global preference for
representative democracy,

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:56.090 align:middle line:10%
the next-best option
is a system where

00:08:56.090 --> 00:08:59.300 align:middle line:10%
experts, not elected
politicians, call the shots.

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:01.460 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:03.260 align:middle line:10%
Praised as the
answer to populism

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:05.930 align:middle line:10%
and political bickering,
more often than not,

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:09.020 align:middle line:10%
technocracies are
temporary solutions.

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:12.480 align:middle line:10%
Their skills complement whatever
crisis a nation is facing.

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:16.100 align:middle line:10%
Or they act as a caretaker
until the next election.

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:19.940 align:middle line:10%
But with democracy under
attack, can unelected experts

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:22.167 align:middle line:10%
rescue a faltering system?

00:09:22.167 --> 00:09:23.750 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Patrick,
this kind of reminds

00:09:23.750 --> 00:09:25.370 align:middle line:90%
me of a New World Order.

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:27.430 align:middle line:84%
>>WOOD: Well, you
could call it that.

00:09:27.430 --> 00:09:32.400 align:middle line:84%
It's been called that, in
fact, now, for 45 years.

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.160 align:middle line:84%
The Trilateral
Commission started off

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:37.010 align:middle line:84%
by calling it the New
International Economic Order.

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:40.400 align:middle line:84%
In 1992, George HW
Bush-- who, by the way,

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:43.340 align:middle line:84%
was a member of the Trilateral
Commission, go figure--

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:47.218 align:middle line:84%
famously said, "the
New World Order."

00:09:47.218 --> 00:09:49.760 align:middle line:84%
That was the first time a member
of the Trilateral Commission

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:55.130 align:middle line:84%
had deviated from "New
International Economic Order."

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:58.160 align:middle line:84%
But ever since then, people
have referred to the New World

00:09:58.160 --> 00:09:59.210 align:middle line:90%
Order.

00:09:59.210 --> 00:10:03.320 align:middle line:84%
